# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: immutable-js
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In object-oriented programming, **object copying** is creating a copy of an existing object, a unit of data in object-oriented programming.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The resulting object is called an *object copy* or simply *copy* of the original object.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Copying is basic but has subtleties and can have significant overhead.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] There are several ways to copy an object, most commonly by a copy constructor or cloning.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Copying is done mostly so the copy can be modified or moved, or the current value preserved.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] If either of these is unneeded, a reference to the original data is sufficient and more efficient, as no copying occurs.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Objects in general store composite data.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] While in simple cases copying can be done by allocating a new, uninitialized object and copying all fields (attributes) from the original object, in more complex cases this does not result in desired behavior.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The design goal of most objects is to give the resemblance of being made out of one monolithic block even though most are not.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] As objects are made up of several different parts, copying becomes nontrivial.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Several strategies exist to treat this problem.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Consider an object A, which contains fields xi (more concretely, consider if A is a string and xi is an array of its characters).
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] There are different strategies for making a copy of A, referred to as *shallow copy* and *deep copy*.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Many languages allow generic copying by one or either strategy, defining either one *copy* operation or separate *shallow copy* and *deep copy* operations.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Note that even shallower is to use a reference to the existing object A, in which case there is no new object, only a new reference.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The terminology of *shallow copy* and *deep copy* dates to Smalltalk-80.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Variables referring to same area of memory.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] One method of copying an object is the *shallow copy*.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In that case a new object B is created, and the fields values of A are copied over to B.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] This is also known as a *field-by-field copy*, *field-for-field copy*, or *field copy*.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] If the field value is a reference to an object (e.g., a memory address) it copies the reference, hence referring to the same object as A does, and if the field value is a primitive type, it copies the value of the primitive type.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In languages without primitive types (where everything is an object), all fields of the copy B are references to the same objects as the fields of original A.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The referenced objects are thus *shared*, so if one of these objects is modified (from A or B), the change is visible in the other.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Shallow copies are simple and typically cheap, as they can usually be implemented by simply copying the bits exactly.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] An alternative is a deep copy, meaning that fields are dereferenced: rather than references to objects being copied, new copy of objects are created for any referenced objects, and references to these are placed in B.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Later modifications to the contents remain unique to A or B, as the contents are not shared.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In more complex cases, some fields in a copy should have shared values with the original object (as in a shallow copy), corresponding to an "association" relationship; some fields should have copies (as in a deep copy), corresponding to an "aggregation" relationship.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In these cases a custom implementation of copying is generally required; this issue and solution dates to Smalltalk-80.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Alternatively, fields can be marked as requiring a shallow copy or deep copy, and copy operations automatically generated (likewise for comparison operations).
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] This is not implemented in most object-oriented languages, however, though there is partial support in Eiffel.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Nearly all object-oriented programming languages provide some way to copy objects.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] As most languages do not provide most objects for programs, a programmer must define how an object should be copied, just as they must define if two objects are identical or even comparable in the first place.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Many languages provide some default behavior.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] How copying is solved varies from language to language, and what concept of an object it has.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] A lazy copy is an implementation of a deep copy.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] When initially copying an object, a (fast) shallow copy is used.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] A counter is also used to track how many objects share the data.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] When the program wants to modify an object, it can determine if the data is shared (by examining the counter) and can do a deep copy if needed.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Lazy copy looks to the outside just as a deep copy, but takes advantage of the speed of a shallow copy whenever possible.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The downside are rather high but constant base costs because of the counter.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Also, in certain situations, circular references can cause problems.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In C++, a lazy copy occurs by default when invoking the copy constructor.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The following presents examples for one of the most widely used object-oriented languages, Java, which should cover nearly every way that an object-oriented language can treat this problem.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Unlike in C++, objects in Java are always accessed indirectly through references.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Objects are never created implicitly but instead are always passed or assigned by a reference variable.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] (Methods in Java are always *pass by value*, however, it is the value of the reference variable that is being passed.) The Java Virtual Machine manages garbage collection so that objects are cleaned up after they are no longer reachable.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] There is no automatic way to copy any given object in Java.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Copying is usually performed by a clone() method of a class.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] This method usually, in turn, calls the clone() method of its parent class to obtain a copy, and then does any custom copying procedures.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Eventually this gets to the clone() method of `Object` (the uppermost class), which creates a new instance of the same class as the object and copies all the fields to the new instance (a "shallow copy").
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] If this method is used, the class must implement the `Cloneable` marker interface, or else it will throw a "Clone Not Supported Exception".
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] After obtaining a copy from the parent class, a class' own clone() method may then provide custom cloning capability, like deep copying (i.e. duplicate some of the structures referred to by the object) or giving the new instance a new unique ID.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The return type of clone() is `Object`, but implementers of a clone method could write the type of the object being cloned instead due to Java's support for covariant return types.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] One advantage of using clone() is that since it is an overridable method, we can call clone() on any object, and it will use the clone() method of its class, without the calling code needing to know what that class is (which would be needed with a copy constructor).
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] A disadvantage is that one often cannot access the clone() method on an abstract type.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Most interfaces and abstract classes in Java do not specify a public clone() method.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Thus, often the only way to use the clone() method is if the class of an object is known, which is contrary to the abstraction principle of using the most generic type possible.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] For example, if one has a List reference in Java, one cannot invoke clone() on that reference because List specifies no public clone() method.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Implementations of List like Array List and Linked List all generally have clone() methods, but it is inconvenient and bad abstraction to carry around the class type of an object.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Another way to copy objects in Java is to serialize them through the `Serializable` interface.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] This is typically used for persistence and wire protocol purposes, but it does create copies of objects and, unlike clone, a deep copy that gracefully handles cycled graphs of objects is readily available with minimal effort from a programmer.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Both of these methods suffer from a notable problem: the constructor is not used for objects copied with clone or serialization.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] This can lead to bugs with improperly initialized data, prevents the use of `final` member fields, and makes maintenance challenging.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Some utilities attempt to overcome these issues by using reflection to deep copy objects, such as the deep-cloning library.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Runtime objects in Eiffel are accessible either indirectly through references or as *expanded* objects which fields are embedded within the objects that use them.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] That is, fields of an object are stored either externally or internally.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The Eiffel class `ANY` contains features for shallow and deep copying and cloning of objects.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] All Eiffel classes inherit from `ANY`, so these features are available within all classes, and are applicable both to reference and expanded objects.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The `copy` feature effects a shallow, field-by-field copy from one object to another.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] If `y` were copied to `x`, then the same objects referenced by `y` before the application of `copy`, will also be referenced by `x` after the `copy` feature completes.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] To effect the creation of a new object which is a shallow duplicate of `y`, the feature `twin` is used.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In this case, one new object is created with its fields identical to those of the source.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The feature `twin` relies on the feature `copy`, which can be redefined in descendants of `ANY`, if needed.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The result of `twin` is of the anchored type `like Current`.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Deep copying and creating deep twins can be done using the features `deep_copy` and `deep_twin`, again inherited from class `ANY`.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] These features have the potential to create many new objects, because they duplicate all the objects in an entire object structure.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Because new duplicate objects are created instead of simply copying references to existing objects, deep operations will become a source of performance issues more readily than shallow operations.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In C#, rather than using the interface `ICloneable`, a generic extension method can be used to create a deep copy using reflection.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] This has two advantages: First, it provides the flexibility to copy every object without having to specify each property and variable to be copied manually.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Second, because the type is generic, the compiler ensures that the destination object and the source object have the same type.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In Objective-C, the methods `copy` and `mutableCopy` are inherited by all objects and intended for performing copies; the latter is for creating a mutable type of the original object.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] These methods in turn call the `copyWithZone` and `mutableCopyWithZone` methods, respectively, to perform the copying.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] An object must implement the corresponding `copyWithZone` method to be copyable.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In OCaml, the library function Oo.copy performs shallow copying of an object.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In Python, the library's copy module provides shallow copy and deep copy of objects through the `copy()` and `deepcopy()` functions, respectively.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Programmers may define special methods `__copy__()` and `__deepcopy__()` in an object to provide custom copying implementation.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In Ruby, all objects inherit two methods for performing shallow copies, clone and dup.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] The two methods differ in that `clone` copies an object's tainted state, frozen state, and any singleton methods it may have, whereas `dup` copies only its tainted state.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Deep copies may be achieved by dumping and loading an object's byte stream or YAML serialization.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] Alternatively, you can use the deep_dive gem to do a controlled deep copy of your object graphs.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In Rust, structs can implement the `clone` method using the `Clone` trait.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In Perl, nested structures are stored by the use of references, thus a developer can either loop over the entire structure and re-reference the data or use the `dclone()` function from the module Storable.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] In VBA, an assignment of variables of type `Object` is a shallow copy, an assignment for all other types (numeric types, String, user defined types, arrays) is a deep copy.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] So the keyword `Set` for an assignment signals a shallow copy and the (optional) keyword `Let` signals a deep copy.
[src:immutable-js/deep-copy] There is no built-in method for deep copies of Objects in VBA.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The **`Map`** object holds key-value pairs and remembers the original insertion order of the keys.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Any value (both objects and primitive values) may be used as either a key or a value.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] `Map` objects are collections of key-value pairs.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] A key in the `Map` **may only occur once**; it is unique in the `Map`'s collection.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] A `Map` object is iterated by key-value pairs — a `for...of` loop returns a 2-member array of `[key, value]` for each iteration.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Iteration happens in *insertion order*, which corresponds to the order in which each key-value pair was first inserted into the map by the `set()` method (that is, there wasn't a key with the same value already in the map when `set()` was called).
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The specification requires maps to be implemented "that, on average, provide access times that are sublinear on the number of elements in the collection".
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Therefore, it could be represented internally as a hash table (with O(1) lookup), a search tree (with O(log(N)) lookup), or any other data structure, as long as the complexity is better than O(N).
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Value equality is based on the SameValueZero algorithm.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] (It used to use SameValue, which treated `0` and `-0` as different.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Check browser compatibility.) This means `NaN` is considered the same as `NaN` (even though `NaN !== NaN`) and all other values are considered equal according to the semantics of the `===` operator.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Also, for object keys, equality is based on object identity.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] They are compared by reference, not by value.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] `Object` is similar to `Map`—both let you set keys to values, retrieve those values, delete keys, and detect whether something is stored at a key.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] For this reason (and because there were no built-in alternatives), `Object` has been used as `Map` historically.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Setting Object properties works for Map objects as well, and can cause considerable confusion.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] But that way of setting a property does not interact with the Map data structure.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] It uses the feature of the generic object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The value of 'bla' is not stored in the Map for queries.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The correct usage for storing data in the Map is through the `set(key, value)` method.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Just like `Map`, entries can be iterated in the same order that they were added to the object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] `Map`-like objects and `Map` also have properties and methods that share the same name and behavior.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] However unlike `Map` they only allow specific predefined types for the keys and values of each entry.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The allowed types are set in the specification IDL definition.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] For example, `RTCStatsReport` is a `Map`-like object that must use strings for keys and objects for values.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] `Map`-like objects are either read-only or read-writable (see the `readonly` keyword in the IDL above).
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The methods and properties have the same behavior as the equivalent entities in `Map`, except for the restriction on the types of the keys and values.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The constructor function that is used to create derived objects.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Groups the elements of a given iterable using the values returned by a provided callback function.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The final returned `Map` uses the unique values from the test function as keys, which can be used to get the array of elements in each group.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] These properties are defined on `Map.prototype` and shared by all `Map` instances.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] For `Map` instances, the initial value is the `Map` constructor.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns the number of key/value pairs in the `Map` object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Map"`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Removes all key-value pairs from the `Map` object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Removes the entry specified by the key from this `Map`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns a new Iterator object that contains a two-member array of `[key, value]` for each element in the `Map` object in insertion order.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Calls `callbackFn` once for each key-value pair present in the `Map` object, in insertion order.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] If a `thisArg` parameter is provided to `forEach`, it will be used as the `this` value for each callback.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns the value corresponding to the key in this `Map`, or `undefined` if there is none.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns the value corresponding to the specified key in this `Map`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] If the key is not present, it inserts a new entry with the key and a given default value, and returns the inserted value.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] If the key is not present, it inserts a new entry with the key and a default value computed from a given callback, and returns the inserted value.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns a boolean indicating whether an entry with the specified key exists in this `Map` or not.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns a new Iterator object that contains the keys for each element in the `Map` object in insertion order.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Adds a new entry with a specified key and value to this `Map`, or updates an existing entry if the key already exists.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-map] Returns a new Iterator object that contains the values for each element in the `Map` object in insertion order.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The **`Set`** object lets you store unique values of any type, whether primitive values or object references.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] `Set` objects are collections of values.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] A value in the set **may only occur once**; it is unique in the set's collection.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] You can iterate through the elements of a set in insertion order.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The *insertion order* corresponds to the order in which each element was inserted into the set by the `add()` method successfully (that is, there wasn't an identical element already in the set when `add()` was called).
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The specification requires sets to be implemented "that, on average, provide access times that are sublinear on the number of elements in the collection".
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The `has` method checks if a value is in the set, using an approach that is, on average, quicker than testing most of the elements that have previously been added to the set.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] In particular, it is, on average, faster than the `Array.prototype.includes` method when an array has a `length` equal to a set's `size`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The `Set` object provides some methods that allow you to compose sets like you would with mathematical operations.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] To make them more generalizable, these methods don't just accept `Set` objects, but anything that's set-like.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] All set composition methods require `this` to be an actual `Set` instance, but their arguments just need to be set-like.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Arrays are not set-like because they don't have a `has()` method or the `size` property, and their `keys()` method produces indices instead of elements.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] `WeakSet` objects are also not set-like because they don't have a `keys()` method.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Browser **`Set`-like objects** (or "setlike objects") are Web API interfaces that behave in many ways like a `Set`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Just like `Set`, elements can be iterated in the same order that they were added to the object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] `Set`-like objects and `Set` also have properties and methods that share the same name and behavior.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] However unlike `Set` they only allow a specific predefined type for each entry.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] For example, `GPUSupportedFeatures` is a `Set`-like object that must use strings as the key/value.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] `Set`-like objects are either read-only or read-writable (see the `readonly` keyword in the IDL above).
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The methods and properties have the same behavior as the equivalent entities in `Set`, except for the restriction on the types of the entry.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] These properties are defined on `Set.prototype` and shared by all `Set` instances.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] For `Set` instances, the initial value is the `Set` constructor.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Returns the number of values in the `Set` object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Set"`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Inserts the specified value into this set, if it is not already present.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Removes all elements from the `Set` object.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Removes the specified value from this set, if it is in the set.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Takes a set and returns a new set containing elements in this set but not in the given set.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Returns a new iterator object that contains **an array of `[value, value]`** for each element in the `Set` object, in insertion order.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] This is similar to the `Map` object, so that each entry's *key* is the same as its *value* for a `Set`.
[src:immutable-js/global-objects-set] Calls `callbackFn` once for each value present in the `Set` object, in insertion order.
