[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable data cannot be changed once created, leading to much simpler application development, no defensive copying, and enabling advanced memoization and change detection techniques with simple logic.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Persistent data presents a mutative API which does not update the data in-place, but instead always yields new updated data.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js provides many Persistent Immutable data structures including: `List`, `Stack`, `Map`, `OrderedMap`, `Set`, `OrderedSet` and `Record`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] These data structures are highly efficient on modern JavaScript VMs by using structural sharing via hash maps tries and vector tries as popularized by Clojure and Scala, minimizing the need to copy or cache data.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js also provides a lazy `Seq`, allowing efficient chaining of collection methods like `map` and `filter` without creating intermediate representations.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Create some `Seq` with `Range` and `Repeat`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js has no dependencies, which makes it predictable to include in a Browser.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] It's highly recommended to use a module bundler like webpack, rollup, or browserify.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The `immutable` npm module works without any additional consideration.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All examples throughout the documentation will assume use of this kind of tool.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Alternatively, Immutable.js may be directly included as a script tag.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Download or link to a CDN such as CDNJS or jsDelivr.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Use these Immutable collections and sequences as you would use native collections in your Flowtype or TypeScript programs while still taking advantage of type generics, error detection, and auto-complete in your IDE.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Installing `immutable` via npm brings with it type definitions for Flow (v0.55.0 or higher) and TypeScript (v4.5 or higher), so you shouldn't need to do anything at all!
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js type definitions embrace ES2015.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] While Immutable.js itself supports legacy browsers and environments, its type definitions require TypeScript's 2015 lib.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Previous versions of Immutable.js include a reference file which you can include via relative path to the type definitions at the top of your file.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Much of what makes application development difficult is tracking mutation and maintaining state.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Developing with immutable data encourages you to think differently about how data flows through your application.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Subscribing to data events throughout your application creates a huge overhead of book-keeping which can hurt performance, sometimes dramatically, and creates opportunities for areas of your application to get out of sync with each other due to easy to make programmer error.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Since immutable data never changes, subscribing to changes throughout the model is a dead-end and new data can only ever be passed from above.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] This model of data flow aligns well with the architecture of React and especially well with an application designed using the ideas of Flux.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] When data is passed from above rather than being subscribed to, and you're only interested in doing work when something has changed, you can use equality.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable collections should be treated as *values* rather than *objects*.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] While objects represent some thing which could change over time, a value represents the state of that thing at a particular instance of time.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] This principle is most important to understanding the appropriate use of immutable data.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] In order to treat Immutable.js collections as values, it's important to use the `Immutable.is()` function or `.equals()` method to determine *value equality* instead of the `===` operator which determines object *reference identity*.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Note: As a performance optimization Immutable.js attempts to return the existing collection when an operation would result in an identical collection, allowing for using `===` reference equality to determine if something definitely has not changed.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] This can be extremely useful when used within a memoization function which would prefer to re-run the function if a deeper equality check could potentially be more costly.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The `===` equality check is also used internally by `Immutable.is` and `.equals()` as a performance optimization.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] If an object is immutable, it can be "copied" simply by making another reference to it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Because a reference is much smaller than the object itself, this results in memory savings and a potential boost in execution speed for programs which rely on copies (such as an undo-stack).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] While Immutable.js is inspired by Clojure, Scala, Haskell and other functional programming environments, it's designed to bring these powerful concepts to JavaScript, and therefore has an Object-Oriented API that closely mirrors that of ES2015 Array, Map, and Set.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The difference for the immutable collections is that methods which would mutate the collection, like `push`, `set`, `unshift` or `splice`, instead return a new immutable collection.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Methods which return new arrays, like `slice` or `concat`, instead return new immutable collections.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Almost all of the methods on Array will be found in similar form on `Immutable.List`, those of Map found on `Immutable.Map`, and those of Set found on `Immutable.Set`, including collection operations like `forEach()` and `map()`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Designed to inter-operate with your existing JavaScript, Immutable.js accepts plain JavaScript Arrays and Objects anywhere a method expects a `Collection`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] This is possible because Immutable.js can treat any JavaScript Array or Object as a Collection.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] You can take advantage of this in order to get sophisticated collection methods on JavaScript Objects, which otherwise have a very sparse native API.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Because Seq evaluates lazily and does not cache intermediate results, these operations can be extremely efficient.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Keep in mind, when using JS objects to construct Immutable Maps, that JavaScript Object properties are always strings, even if written in a quote-less shorthand, while Immutable Maps accept keys of any type.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Property access for JavaScript Objects first converts the key to a string, but since Immutable Map keys can be of any type the argument to `get()` is not altered.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All Immutable.js Collections can be converted to plain JavaScript Arrays and Objects shallowly with `toArray()` and `toObject()` or deeply with `toJS()`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All Immutable Collections also implement `toJSON()` allowing them to be passed to `JSON.stringify` directly.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] They also respect the custom `toJSON()` methods of nested objects.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js supports all JavaScript environments, including legacy browsers (even IE11).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] However it also takes advantage of features added to JavaScript in ES2015, the latest standard version of JavaScript, including Iterators, Arrow Functions, Classes, and Modules.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] It's inspired by the native Map and Set collections added to ES2015.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All examples in the Documentation are presented in ES2015.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] To run in all browsers, they need to be translated to ES5.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All Immutable.js collections are Iterable, which allows them to be used anywhere an Iterable is expected, such as when spreading into an Array.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Note: A Collection is always iterated in the same order, however that order may not always be well defined, as is the case for the `Map` and `Set`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The collections in Immutable.js are intended to be nested, allowing for deep trees of data, similar to JSON.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] A few power-tools allow for reading and operating on nested data.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The most useful are `mergeDeep`, `getIn`, `setIn`, and `updateIn`, found on `List`, `Map` and `OrderedMap`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js collections are treated as pure data *values*.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Two immutable collections are considered *value equal* (via `.equals()` or `is()`) if they represent the same collection of values.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] This differs from JavaScript's typical *reference equal* (via `===` or `==`) for Objects and Arrays which only determines if two variables represent references to the same object instance.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Consider the example below where two identical `Map` instances are not *reference equal* but are *value equal*.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Note: `is()` uses the same measure of equality as Object.is for scalar strings and numbers, but uses value equality for Immutable collections, determining if both are immutable and all keys and values are equal using the same measure of equality.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] While value equality is useful in many circumstances, it has different performance characteristics than reference equality.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Understanding these tradeoffs may help you decide which to use in each case, especially when used to memoize some operation.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] When comparing two collections, value equality may require considering every item in each collection, on an `O(N)` time complexity.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] For large collections of values, this could become a costly operation.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Though if the two are not equal and hardly similar, the inequality is determined very quickly.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] In contrast, when comparing two collections with reference equality, only the initial references to memory need to be compared which is not based on the size of the collections, which has an `O(1)` time complexity.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Checking reference equality is always very fast, however just because two collections are not reference-equal does not rule out the possibility that they may be value-equal.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] When possible, Immutable.js avoids creating new objects for updates where no change in *value* occurred, to allow for efficient *reference equality* checking to quickly determine if no change occurred.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] However updates which do result in a change will return a new reference.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Applying a mutation to create a new immutable object results in some overhead, which can add up to a minor performance penalty.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] If you need to apply a series of mutations locally before returning, Immutable.js gives you the ability to create a temporary mutable (transient) copy of a collection and apply a batch of mutations in a performant manner by using `withMutations`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] In fact, this is exactly how Immutable.js applies complex mutations itself.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] As an example, building `list2` results in the creation of 1, not 3, new immutable Lists.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Note: Immutable.js also provides `asMutable` and `asImmutable`, but only encourages their use when `withMutations` will not suffice.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Use caution to not return a mutable copy, which could result in undesired behavior.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] `Seq` describes a lazy operation, allowing them to efficiently chain use of all the higher-order collection methods (such as `map` and `filter`) by not creating intermediate collections.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Once the `Seq` is used, it performs only the work necessary.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Any collection can be converted to a lazy Seq with `Seq()`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] As well as expressing logic that would otherwise seem memory or time limited, for example `Range` is a special kind of Lazy sequence.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The `filter()`, `groupBy()`, and `partition()` methods are similar in that they all divide a collection into parts based on applying a function to each element.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All three call the predicate or grouping function once for each item in the input collection.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] All three return zero or more collections of the same type as their input.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The returned collections are always distinct from the input (according to `===`), even if the contents are identical.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Of these methods, `filter()` is the only one that is lazy and the only one which discards items from the input collection.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] It is the simplest to use, and the fact that it returns exactly one collection makes it easy to combine with other methods to form a pipeline of operations.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The `partition()` method is similar to an eager version of `filter()`, but it returns two collections; the first contains the items that would have been discarded by `filter()`, and the second contains the items that would have been kept.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] It always returns an array of exactly two collections, which can make it easier to use than `groupBy()`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Compared to making two separate calls to `filter()`, `partition()` makes half as many calls it the predicate passed to it.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] The `groupBy()` method is a more generalized version of `partition()` that can group by an arbitrary function rather than just a predicate.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] It returns a map with zero or more entries, where the keys are the values returned by the grouping function, and the values are nonempty collections of the corresponding arguments.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Although `groupBy()` is more powerful than `partition()`, it can be harder to use because it is not always possible predict in advance how many entries the returned map will have and what their keys will be.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Have an additional tool designed to work with Immutable.js?
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Submit a PR to add it to this list in alphabetical order.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] We actively welcome pull requests, learn how to contribute.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Immutable.js is maintained within the Contributor Covenant's Code of Conduct.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Phil Bagwell, for his inspiration and research in persistent data structures.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] Hugh Jackson, for providing the npm package name.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-js-com] If you're looking for his unsupported package, see this repository.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In object-oriented (OO) and functional programming, an **immutable object** (unchangeable object) is an object whose state cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] This is in contrast to a **mutable object** (changeable object), which can be modified after it is created.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In some cases, an object is considered immutable even if some internally used attributes change, but the object's state appears unchanging from an external point of view.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] For example, an object that uses memoization to cache the results of expensive computations could still be considered an immutable object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Strings and other concrete objects are typically expressed as immutable objects to improve readability and runtime efficiency in object-oriented programming.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Immutable objects are also useful because they are inherently thread-safe.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Other benefits are that they are simpler to understand and reason about and offer higher security than mutable objects.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In imperative programming, values held in program variables whose content never changes are known as *constants* to differentiate them from variables that could be altered during execution.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Examples include conversion factors from meters to feet, or the value of pi to several decimal places.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Read-only fields may be calculated when the program runs (unlike constants, which are known beforehand), but never change after they are initialized.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Sometimes, one talks of certain *fields* of an object being immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] This means that there is no way to change those parts of the object state, even though other parts of the object may be changeable (*weakly immutable*).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If all fields are immutable, then the object is immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If the whole object cannot be extended by another class, the object is called *strongly immutable*.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] This might, for example, help to explicitly enforce certain invariants about certain data in the object staying the same through the lifetime of the object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In some languages, this is done with a keyword (e.g.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] `const` in C++, `final` in Java) that designates the field as immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Some languages reverse it: in OCaml, fields of an object or record are by default immutable, and must be explicitly marked with `mutable` to be so.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In most object-oriented languages, objects can be referred to using references.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Some examples of such languages are Java, C++, C#, VB.NET, and many scripting languages, such as Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In this case, it matters whether the state of an object can vary when objects are shared via references.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If an object is known to be immutable, it is preferred to create a reference of it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] This is done to conserve memory by preventing data duplication and avoid calls to constructors and destructors; it also results in a potential boost in execution speed.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The reference copying technique is much more difficult to use for mutable objects, because if any user of a mutable object reference changes it, all other users of that reference see the change.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If this is not the intended effect, it can be difficult to notify the other users to have them respond correctly.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In these situations, defensive copying of the entire object rather than the reference is usually an easy but costly solution.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The observer pattern is an alternative technique for handling changes to mutable objects.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] A technique that blends the advantages of **mutable** and **immutable** objects, and is supported directly in almost all modern hardware, is copy-on-write (COW).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Using this technique, when a user asks the system to copy an object, it instead merely creates a new reference that still points to the same object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] As soon as a user attempts to modify the object through a particular reference, the system makes a real copy, applies the modification to that, and sets the reference to refer to the new copy.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The other users are unaffected, because they still refer to the original object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Therefore, under COW, all users appear to have a mutable version of their objects, although in the case that users do not modify their objects, the space-saving and speed advantages of immutable objects are preserved.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Copy-on-write is popular in virtual memory systems because it allows them to save memory space while still correctly handling anything an application program might do.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The practice of always using references in place of copies of equal objects is known as *interning*.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If interning is used, two objects are considered equal if and only if their references, typically represented as pointers or integers, are equal.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Some languages do this automatically: for example, Python automatically interns short strings.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If the algorithm that implements interning is guaranteed to do so in every case that it is possible, then comparing objects for equality is reduced to comparing their pointers – a substantial gain in speed in most applications.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] (Even if the algorithm is not guaranteed to be comprehensive, there still exists the possibility of a fast path case improvement when the objects are equal and use the same reference.) Interning is generally only useful for immutable objects.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Immutable objects can be useful in multi-threaded applications.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Multiple threads can act on data represented by immutable objects without concern of the data being changed by other threads.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Immutable objects are therefore considered more *thread-safe* than mutable objects.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Immutability does not imply that the object as stored in the computer's memory is unwriteable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Rather, immutability is a compile-time construct that indicates what a programmer can do through the normal interface of the object, not necessarily what they can absolutely do (for instance, by circumventing the type system or violating const correctness in C or C++).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In Python, Java and the .NET Framework, strings are immutable objects.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Both Java and the .NET Framework have mutable versions of string.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In Java these are `StringBuffer` and `StringBuilder` (mutable versions of Java `String`) and in .NET this is `StringBuilder` (mutable version of .Net `String`).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Python 3 has a mutable string (bytes) variant, named `bytearray`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Additionally, all of the primitive wrapper classes in Java are immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Similar patterns are the Immutable Interface and Immutable Wrapper.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In pure functional programming languages it is not possible to create mutable objects without extending the language (e.g. via a mutable references library or a foreign function interface), so all objects are immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In Ada, any object is declared either *variable* (i.e. mutable; typically the implicit default), or `constant` (i.e. immutable) via the `constant` keyword.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Subprogram parameters are immutable in the *in* mode, and mutable in the *in out* and *out* modes.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In C# one can enforce immutability of the fields of a class with the `readonly` statement.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] By enforcing all the fields as immutable, the type becomes an immutable type.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In C++, a const-correct implementation of `ShoppingCart` would allow the user to create instances of the class and then use them as either `const` (immutable) or mutable, as desired, by providing two different versions of the `items()` method.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Note that, when there is a data member that is a pointer or reference to another object, then it is possible to mutate the object pointed to or referenced only within a non-const method.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] C++ also provides abstract (as opposed to bitwise) immutability via the `mutable` keyword, which lets a member variable be changed from within a `const` method.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In D, there exist two type qualifiers, `const` and `immutable`, for variables that cannot be changed.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Unlike C++'s `const`, Java's `final`, and C#'s `readonly`, they are transitive and recursively apply to anything reachable through references of such a variable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The difference between `const` and `immutable` is what they apply to: `const` is a property of the variable: there might legally exist mutable references to referred value, i.e. the value can actually change.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In contrast, `immutable` is a property of the referred value: the value and anything transitively reachable from it cannot change (without breaking the type system, leading to undefined behavior).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Any reference of that value must be marked `const` or `immutable`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Basically for any unqualified type `T`, `const(T)` is the disjoint union of `T` (mutable) and `immutable(T)`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] For a mutable `Example` object, its `mutableField` can be written to.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] For a `const(Example)` object, `mutableField` cannot be modified, it inherits `const`; `immutableField` is still immutable as it is the stronger guarantee.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] For an `immutable(Example)`, all fields are immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Inside the braces, `c` might refer to the same object as `m`, so mutations to `m` could indirectly change `c` as well.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Also, `c` might refer to the same object as `i`, but since the value then is immutable, there are no changes.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] However, `m` and `i` cannot legally refer to the same object.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In the language of guarantees, mutable has no guarantees (the function might change the object), `const` is an outward-only guarantee that the function will not change anything, and `immutable` is a bidirectional guarantee (the function will not change the value and the caller must not change it).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Values that are `const` or `immutable` must be initialized by direct assignment at the point of declaration or by a constructor.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Because `const` parameters forget if the value was mutable or not, a similar construct, `inout`, acts, in a sense, as a variable for mutability information.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] A function of type `const(S) function(const(T))` returns `const(S)` typed values for mutable, const and immutable arguments.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In contrast, a function of type `inout(S) function(inout(T))` returns `S` for mutable `T` arguments, `const(S)` for `const(T)` values, and `immutable(S)` for `immutable(T)` values.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Casting immutable values to mutable inflicts undefined behavior upon change, even if the original value comes from a mutable origin.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Casting mutable values to immutable can be legal when there remain no mutable references afterward.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The type `string` is an alias for `immutable(char)[]`, i.e. a typed slice of memory of immutable characters.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Making substrings is cheap, as it just copies and modifies a pointer and a length filed, and safe, as the underlying data cannot be changed.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Objects of type `const(char)[]` can refer to strings, but also to mutable buffers.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Making a shallow copy of a const or immutable value removes the outer layer of immutability: Copying an immutable string (`immutable(char[])`) returns a string (`immutable(char)[]`).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The immutable pointer and length are being copied and the copies are mutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The referred data has not been copied and keeps its qualifier, in the example `immutable`.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] It can be stripped by making a depper copy, e.g. using the `dup` function.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The method `toLowerCase()` does not change the data "ABC" that `s` contains.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Instead, a new String object is instantiated and given the data "abc" during its construction.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] A reference to this String object is returned by the `toLowerCase()` method.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Now the String `s` references a new String object that contains "abc".
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] There is nothing in the syntax of the *declaration* of the class String that enforces it as immutable; rather, none of the String class's methods ever affect the data that a String object contains, thus making it immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The keyword `final` (detailed article) is used in implementing immutable primitive types and object references, but it cannot, by itself, make *the objects themselves* immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Primitive type variables (`int`, `long`, `short`, etc.) can be reassigned after being defined.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Reference types cannot be made immutable just by using the `final` keyword.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Primitive wrappers (`Integer`, `Long`, `Short`, `Double`, `Float`, `Character`, `Byte`, `Boolean`) are also all immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Immutable classes can be implemented by following a few simple guidelines.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In JavaScript, all primitive types (Undefined, Null, Boolean, Number, BigInt, String, Symbol) are immutable, but custom objects are generally mutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] To simulate immutability in an object, one may define properties as read-only (writable: false).
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] However, the approach above still lets new properties be added.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Alternatively, one may use Object.freeze to make existing objects immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] With the implementation of ECMA262, JavaScript has the ability to create immutable references that cannot be reassigned.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] However, using a `const` declaration doesn't mean that value of the read-only reference is immutable, just that the name cannot be assigned to a new value.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The use of immutable state has become a rising trend in JavaScript since the introduction of React, which favours Flux-like state management patterns such as Redux.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In PHP have readonly properties since version 8.1 and readonly classes since version 8.2.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In Python, some built-in types (numbers, Booleans, strings, tuples, frozensets) are immutable, but custom classes are generally mutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The standard library helpers `collections.namedtuple` and `typing.NamedTuple`, available from Python 3.6 onward, create simple immutable classes.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Introduced in Python 3.7, `dataclasses` allow developers to emulate immutability with frozen instances.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] If a frozen dataclass is built, `dataclasses` will override `__setattr__()` and `__delattr__()` to raise `FrozenInstanceError` if invoked.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Racket substantially diverges from other Scheme implementations by making its core pair type ("cons cells") immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Instead, it provides a parallel mutable pair type, via `mcons`, `mcar`, `set-mcar!` etc.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In addition, many immutable types are supported, for example, immutable strings and vectors, and these are used extensively.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] The language also supports immutable hash tables, implemented functionally, and immutable dictionaries.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Rust's ownership system allows developers to declare immutable variables, and pass immutable references.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] By default, all variables and references are immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Mutable variables and references are explicitly created with the `mut` keyword.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Constant items in Rust are always immutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] In Scala, any entity (narrowly, a binding) can be defined as mutable or immutable: in the declaration, one can use `val` (value) for immutable entities and `var` (variable) for mutable ones.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] Note that even though an immutable binding can not be reassigned, it may still refer to a mutable object and it is still possible to call mutating methods on that object: the *binding* is immutable, but the underlying *object* may be mutable.
[src:immutable-js/immutable-object] defines an immutable entity `maxValue` (the integer type is inferred at compile-time) and a mutable entity named `currentValue`.
